This paper deals with the use of artificial neural networks for predicting the occupancy state of a scene based on radar measurements. This involves computer vision (CV) techniques for processing the radar data and machine learning (ML) techniques for training the neural networks. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on driver assistance technology, which falls under the category of robotics (RO), making cs.RO the second most likely sub-category. The use of ML techniques for predicting occupancy state also falls under the category of artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.AI a likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of spatial priors and large-scale mapping applications, which involve natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (CL) techniques, making cs.CL a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of ML techniques for predicting occupancy state, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category.
